#Text=Juan de Silva

#Text=Juan de Silva ( died April 19 , 1616 , Malacca ) was a Spanish military commander and governor of the Philippines , from April 1609 until his death on April 19 , 1616 .
#Text=De Silva was a native of Trujillo , Spain , and a knight of the Order of Santiago .
#Text=He arrived in the Philippines as governor and captain general at Easter , 1609 , bring with him five companies of reinforcements for the Spanish military in the colony .
#Text=He developed a reputation for bravery and determination in his fight with the Dutch in the Far East .
#Text=Defeat of the Dutch at Manila
#Text=On December 22 , 1607 a Dutch fleet of the Company of the East Indies set sail from Texel to attack the Portuguese fleet and forts in the East .
#Text=The fleet consisted of 13 vessels , 225 artillery pieces and more than 2,800 men .
#Text=It was under the command of Admiral Pierre Willemsz . , with François de Wittert as vice-admiral .
#Text=The fleet fought with the Portuguese in Mozambique , Sumatra and Johore before building a fort at Near , in the Banda Islands ( present-day Indonesia ) .
#Text=Here on May 22 , 1609 the admiral and some of his officers were killed in an attack by the natives , and Wittert assumed command .
#Text=Thereafter Wittert sailed to Manila to attack the Spanish there .
#Text=( Spain and Portugal were ruled by the same king , Philip III of Spain ( Philip II of Portugal ) , and thus were allies . ) Wittert besieged Manila for five months , beginning in 1609 .
#Text=However , on April 24 or April 25 , 1610 , while supervising the unloading of junks , Wittert was surprised by at least 12 Spanish ships .
#Text=His flagship , the Amsterdam , was captured after a lengthy fight , and the admiral was killed .
#Text=Two ships apparently escaped , but the Spanish killed at least 85 Dutch and took 120 or more prisoners .
#Text=Also during the first part of Governor de Silva 's term , the fourth archbishop of Manila , Diego Vazquez de Mercado , arrived there ( June 4 , 1610 ) .
#Text=Expeditions to the Moluccas
#Text=De Silva sent an unsuccessful expedition against the Dutch in the Moluccas in 1611 , although the expedition did take Sabougo on Gilolo and establish a fort there .
#Text=De Silva intended to secure Portuguese help to expel the Dutch from the area once and for all .
#Text=To this end in 1612 he dispatched the former governor of Ternate , Cristobal de Azcueta to Portuguese India to make plans with the viceroy there for a joint assault .
#Text=However Azcueta and the entire expedition were lost in a shipwreck between Manila and Macao .
#Text=De Silva tried again , this time sending two Jesuit emissaries to Goa .
#Text=They arrived in 1615 and reached an agreement with the Portuguese viceroy that he would contribute four large galleons , to be sent to Malacca .
#Text=This information was received in Manila , where a large Spanish fleet was already prepared , in July 1615 .
#Text=In order to obtain the artillery for this expedition de Silva had weakened the defenses of Manila , with grave risks in the event of an attack on the city by the Dutch .
#Text=There was no news of the arrival of the Portuguese galleons , but against the advice of many of his subordinates , Governor de Silva sailed for Malacca on February 9 , 1616 .
#Text=He commanded ten galleons , four galleys and various smaller vessels .
#Text=The flagship was the 1,700-ton San Marcos .
#Text=The fleet carried 5,000 men , both soldiers and sailors , including nearly 2,000 Spaniards and a unit of Japanese infantry , which numbered at 500 .
#Text=It also carried 300 artillery pieces and 6 Jesuits .
#Text=It was the largest European armada yet seen in the region .

#Text=The fleet sailed for the Strait of Malacca , with the intention of uniting with the expected Portuguese armada and then attacking the Dutch factory on Java and thereafter the Dutch bases on the islands of the Moluccas .
#Text=But the Portuguese fleet had already been attacked by the Dutch near Malacca and completely destroyed .
#Text=In order to avoid their capture , the Portuguese had burned their big galleons .
#Text=The Spanish fleet entered the Strait of Singapore on February 25 , 1616 .
#Text=From there Governor de Silva sent Juan Gutierrez Paramo with part of the fleet to reinforce Ternate ( in the Moluccas ) .
#Text=But the governor was in poor health .
#Text=He had earlier asked several times to be relieved of office for health reasons .
#Text=Now his health deteriorated further , and on April 19 , 1616 , he died in Malacca .
#Text=The whole Spanish enterprise had to be abandoned , with nothing accomplished against the Dutch .
#Text=The armada returned to Manila on June 1 , 1616 , sin gente ( without people ) .
#Text=Although they had not faced combat , many men had died of fevers and other illnesses that struck the fleet in Malacca and the Strait of Singapore .

#Text=Critics of the governor , both among his contemporaries and later historians , have claimed that had he sailed directly to the Moluccas rather than to Malacca , he very possibly could have dislodged the undermanned Dutch from the archipelago .
#Text=After his death
#Text=The Audiencia of Manila took charge of political affairs in the absence of Juan de Silva .
#Text=Jerónimo de Silva , an uncle of the governor , was made interim governor by a royal decree in March 1616 .
#Text=The Audiencia governed until June or July , 1618 , when the new governor , Alonso Fajardo y Tenza arrived and took up office .
